entity.name: Philip E. Tetlock
entity.text:
Philip Eyrikson Tetlock (born March 2, 1954) is a Canadian-American political psychologist and writer, and is currently the Annenberg University Professor at the University of Pennsylvania, where he is cross-appointed at the Wharton School and the School of Arts and Sciences. He was elected a Member of the American Philosophical Society in 2019. [...] ## Biography

[edit]

Tetlock was born in Toronto, Canada and grew up in Winnipeg and Vancouver. He studied psychology at the University of British Columbia, where he received a B.A. in 1975 and an M.A. in 1976. He worked with Peter Suedfeld during his master's study on content analysis of diplomatic communications. He then moved to the US and conducted his doctoral research at Yale University, obtaining his PhD in psychology in 1979. His thesis was supervised by Phoebe C. Ellsworth. [...] | Tetlock at the 2017 World Economic Forum |
| Born | (1954-03-02) March 2, 1954 (age 71)  Toronto, Ontario, Canada |
| Alma mater | University of British Columbia (BA, MA) Yale University (PhD) |
| Scientific career |
| Fields | political forecasting, political psychology, forecasting, decision making |
| Institutions | University of Pennsylvania University of California, Berkeley Ohio State University |
| Thesis | Attributions As Interpersonal Acts (1979) |
